      {
         "id": "SECTION_images",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Images from Antropology Peru\n\nThese images are copyright for Antropology Peru and allowed to be used according to the license determined by them.\n\nTo visualize all images, use the left and right arrows on the slide below.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htSlides\"><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">1 / 1</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"img4\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img4', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Representation of a ruler measuring a line. The source code is available on the project’s GitHub (<htcite0>).</div><div class=\"htSlideRefs\"><b>Related content:</b><ul><li>Couting (First Steps (Volume 1)) (<htcite1>)</li><li>Rereading (First Steps (Volume 1)) (<htcite2>)</li><li>Understanding the Multiplication Table (2 and 3) (First Steps (Volume 1)) (<htcite3>)</li><li>Understanding the Multiplication Table (4 and 5) (First Steps (Volume 1)) (<htcite4>)</li><li>Understanding the Multiplication Table (8 and 9) (First Steps (Volume 1)) (<htcite5>)</li><li>Understanding Texts: Equality Levels - Some concepts, like the definition of a planet, change over time. Sometimes, objects with slightly different sizes can be considered equal. How can we use numbers to quantify equality? (<htcite6>)</li><li>Mathematical Games: Change of direction (Part I) - We study the logic behind the different approach used by indigenous communities as their numbers grow.. (<htcite7>)</li><li>Mathematical Games: Change of direction (Part II) - Building on the previous discussion, this section explores how indigenous peoples represent large numbers. (<htcite8>)</li><li>Mathematical Games: Drawing to count - Exploring how indigenous peoples developed methods for counting. (<htcite9>)</li><li>Myths and Believes: 1 + 1 = 2? - It is tempting to answer this question right away, but it is always important to first ask what exactly we are adding before giving the answer. (<htcite10>)</li><li>Myths and Believes: Are addition and multiplication independent operations? - Often, the way mathematics is taught leads to a mistaken understanding of multiplication. In reality, multiplication can be understood as the repeated addition of the same quantity. (<htcite11>)</li><li>Physics: Continuity - When we look around us and at ourselves, we don't see gaps everywhere. In this text, we begin to see how to connect things. (<htcite14>)</li><li>Physics: Reality - When we insert decimal numbers between integers, we cease to merely count in order to understand reality. (<htcite12>)</li><li>Physics: Simplicity vs. Complexity - Despite more than 13.8 billion years of evolution of the universe, we often still wish to be like it was in its beginnings. Why? (<htcite13>)</li></ul></div></div><i class=\"fa-solid fa-chevron-left htSlidePrev\" onclick=\"htPlusDivs(-1);\"></i><i class=\"fa-solid fa-chevron-right htSlideNext\" onclick=\"htPlusDivs(1);\"></i></div></p>",
